#X obj 176 192 adsr~ 50 15 0.75 750;
#X text 293 399 One could also think about an attack and release envelope for filtering \, but just a release has a nice feel that makes it sound less brigth when releasing the envelope., f 44;
#X obj 84 306 rescale~ -in 0 1 50 100, f 8;
#X obj 84 363 mtof~;
#X text 293 466 In this example \, for the sake of simplicity \, we have a fixed cutoff frequency at MIDI pitch '50' (D3 \, close to 150hz) and the maximum modulated cutoff is 100 (about 2.6 Khz)., f 44;
#X obj 84 258 glide2~ 0 750, f 7;
#X text 293 233 We can use a simpler envelope than an ADSR for the envelope \, just like we can use more complicated ones. In this example we have a very simple envelope that just has a release stage with [glide2~]. The [asr~] could also be used instead of [adsr~] because we don't need the decay and sustain stages for this \, but one could also use [adsr~] by adjusting attack/decay to zero and the sustain point to 1! We still have a proper [adsr~] for the amplitude., f 44;
